C++ STL COMPARISON SHEET (ONE-DAY REVISION)
=========================================

This sheet helps quickly revise differences between major STL containers.

=========================================
1. MAP vs UNORDERED_MAP
=========================================

MAP
----
- Implemented as Red-Black Tree (Self balancing BST)
- Stores key in sorted order
- Time Complexity:
  insert    O(log n)
  erase     O(log n)
  find      O(log n)

- Ordered output: YES

Example:
map<int,int> m;

Use when:
✓ Need sorted keys
✓ Range queries (lower_bound, upper_bound)

-----------------------------------------

UNORDERED_MAP
--------------
- Implemented using Hash Table
- No ordering of keys
- Time Complexity:
  insert    O(1) average
  erase     O(1) average
  find      O(1) average

Worst case: O(n)

Example:
unordered_map<int,int> um;

Use when:
✓ Fast lookup needed
✓ No ordering required

-----------------------------------------

INTERVIEW ONE-LINER:
map = sorted (tree)
unordered_map = fastest lookup (hash)

=========================================
2. SET vs UNORDERED_SET
=========================================

SET
---
- Red-Black Tree
- Stores unique sorted elements
- O(log n) operations

Use when:
✓ Sorted unique values needed
✓ Lower/upper bound required

-----------------------------------------

UNORDERED_SET
-------------
- Hash Table
- Unique elements only
- O(1) average operations

Use when:
✓ Fast membership check
✓ Order not required

-----------------------------------------

INTERVIEW ONE-LINER:
set = ordered unique
unordered_set = fast unique lookup

=========================================
3. LIST vs VECTOR vs DEQUE
=========================================

VECTOR
------
- Contiguous memory
- Dynamic array
- Fast random access O(1)
- push_back O(1) amortized
- insert front O(n)

Use when:
✓ Mostly sequential data
✓ Cache performance important

-----------------------------------------

LIST
----
- Doubly linked list
- Non-contiguous memory
- No random access
- insert/erase O(1) (if iterator known)

Use when:
✓ Frequent middle insert/delete
✓ Iterator stability required

-----------------------------------------

DEQUE
-----
- Multiple memory blocks
- Double ended queue
- push_front O(1)
- push_back O(1)
- random access O(1)

Use when:
✓ Need operations at both ends

-----------------------------------------

INTERVIEW ONE-LINER:
vector = fastest traversal
list = fastest middle insertion
deque = best for both ends

=========================================
4. STACK vs QUEUE vs PRIORITY_QUEUE
=========================================

STACK
-----
- LIFO
- top() access only
- Uses deque internally
- push/pop O(1)

Use:
DFS, recursion, backtracking

-----------------------------------------

QUEUE
-----
- FIFO
- front/back access
- Uses deque internally
- push/pop O(1)

Use:
BFS, scheduling

-----------------------------------------

PRIORITY_QUEUE
--------------
- Heap based structure (Max Heap by default)
- Largest element always on top

Operations:
push    O(log n)
pop     O(log n)
top     O(1)

Use:
✓ Top K problems
✓ Dijkstra algorithm
✓ Greedy problems

Min Heap:
priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> pq;

-----------------------------------------

INTERVIEW ONE-LINER:
stack = LIFO
queue = FIFO
priority_queue = heap (max element first)

=========================================
5. SET vs MAP (VERY IMPORTANT)
=========================================

SET
---
- Stores only keys
- Unique values

MAP
---
- Stores key-value pairs
- Unique keys

Example:
set<int> s;
map<int,int> m;

-----------------------------------------

INTERVIEW:
set = just keys
map = key + value

